@node Introduction

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

  When booting a machine with Kickstart 2 or above, the screen
  is blank, and rather dull.
  
  BootPicture displays a nice picture, and automatically closes it
  when the workbench screen opens.

@endnode

@node Features
@next Arguments

@{b}Features@{ub}

  There are numerous other programs which do something similar.

  Bootpicture has :-

	* AGA and ECS versions.  @{" More " link More_ECS_AGA}
	* Stylish and beautiful pictures by @{"Joshua B. Wingell" link "Authors" 30},
	  and @{"Michael Becker" link "Authors" 30}
	* Senses PAL or NTSC, and centers the picture accordingly.  @{" More " link More_NTSC_PAL}
	* Self detaching.  @{" More " link More_Runback}
	* Self contained.  @{" More " link More_Contained}
	  - Easy installation
	  - Avoids disk thrashing
	  - Automatic shut down

@endnode

@node More_ECS_AGA "Features: ECS and AGA versions"

@{b}Feature: ECS and AGA versions@{ub}

  ECS Versions (16 colours):
    BootPaintPicture     @{" Test " SYSTEM "BootPaint_ECS/BootPicture"}
    AmigaTechnologies    @{" Test " SYSTEM "Amiga_ECS/BootPicture"}
    MacOS                @{" Test " SYSTEM "MacOS_ECS/BootPicture"}

  AGA Versions (256 colours):
    AmigaTechnologies    @{" Test " SYSTEM "Amiga_AGA/BootPicture"}
    MacOS                @{" Test " SYSTEM "MacOS_AGA/BootPicture"}

  The ECS versions run OK on an AGA Amiga too.

  Note : The top of the workbench screen will be visible at the top.
  This will NOT appear when run from your startup-sequence, as the
  workbench screen will not have been opened yet.

  Note : To quit, use LeftAmiga-M

@endnode

@node More_NTSC_PAL "Features: NTSC and PAL switching"

@{b}Feature: NTSC and PAL switching@{ub}

  Under kickstart 2, you can boot the machine in either PAL or NTSC
  modes, using the early start boot menu (hold down both mouse buttons
  as you turn on).

  I havent actually needed to use this myself, but it was only one
  and a half lines of code, and made it usable to people in the
  United States of America too.

@endnode

@node More_RunBack "Features: Autodetaching"

@{b}Feature: Autodetaching@{ub}

  The program automatically detaches itself from the shell, without
openening stdio, so there is no need to use @{b}run <NIL: >NIL@{ub}, and
it wont prevent the Shell window from closing, should it open.

@endnode

@node More_Contained "Features: Self contained"

@{b}Feature: Self contained@{ub}

  Bootpicture is entirely self contained in one executable - "BootPicture".
  It does not require a configuration file, or a preference program,
  or any libraries other than those built into your Amiga.  The picture
  is also built into this executable.

  Why is this good?

  1) It is simple to install.  No command line options to foul things up.
  No unnecessary files in envarc: or libs: or s:.  Only ONE modification
  to your startup-sequence.

  2) Other programs show a picture for a predetermined time, so you
  would have to use a stopwatch to time how long your machine takes
  to start up!  So whenever you add more stuff to your startup-sequence,
  you would have to re-time how long it takes to startup!  Thats just
  silly.
  BootPicture avoids this problem, by finishing when the workbench
  screen opens.

  3) Other programs require you to install a second command in you
  WBStartUp drawer, or at the end of your startup-sequence to tell
  it to remove the picture.  What happens if theres a problem starting
  up????
  Bootpicture does not suffer from this.  Its automatic.

  4) Other programs require you to specify the picture to load.  This
  means that while your amiga continues with the startup-sequence,
  those other programs are trying to load the picture from a different
  part of the disk, which can result in disk thrashing, which reduces
  the speed at which you machine boots up.
  Bootpicture does not suffer from this.  Its all built in.

  See @{" Arguments " link "Arguments"}

@endnode

@node Arguments "Reasons for not using BootPicture"
@prev Features

@{b}Arguments against BootPicture@{ub}

  1) "Look at the size of the executable!  Its huge!"
  Response:  thats it.  Code + picture.  No hidden extras.  No libraries
  to open (eg IFFPARSE, IFF).  No external picture to load into memory.
  No picture decoding code.  Add it all up, and bootpicture is smaller.

  2) "It only shows one picture!"
  Response:  I've only found _TWO_ pictures which are sufficiently
  stylish and elegant for my Amiga.  Besides, I've included the source
  code for BootPaintPicture, and I've uploaded the others to Aminet as
  @{b}util/boot/BootPicture-src.lha@{ub}.  If you come across any quality
  pictures, why not share them with the rest of the Amiga community?

  3) "I want it to display my machine configuration!"
  Response:  Load the picture into Personal Paint, and use the TEXT tool.
  "But I want it to be automatic!"
  Response: Seriously, how often do you change your cpu/mmu/fpu/memory
  configuration?  If you have enough money to be changing your
  set up every few weeks, then you dont need a fast, sleek and elegant
  boot time picture displayer.  Use one of the others.

@endnode

@node Requirements

@{b}Requirements@{ub}

    This program needs Amiga OS 2.0+.

    A Hard Disk is highly recommended, but can work on floppy disk
    systems.

@endnode

@node Installation

@{b}Installation@{ub}

  Installing is simple!

  1) Just copy the program to your C: directory
  2) Edit your S:Startup-Sequence.
     Just after SetPatch, insert the command

           @{b}C:BootPicture@{ub}


@endnode

@node Bugs "Known bugs"

@{b}Known Bugs@{ub}

	* It crashes if run from workbench.  It was always meant to
	  be run from the shell anyway.

@endnode

@node History

@{b}History@{ub}

  1.00	    1995  Wojciech Jeczmien.
	- First Version, and original program concept

  1.50	May 1996  Tak Tang.
	- Fixed bug involving the bottom and right edges being chopped off
	- Optimised the number of windows opened
	- Reduced screen size to size of picture
	- Added NTSC/PAL switching
	- Produced AmigaTech and MacOS version, in AGA and ECS editions

@endnode

@node Future

@{b}Future@{ub}

  This program was developed for my needs.  I wanted a program which
  was simple and elegant.  Any future developments are likely to
  be prompted by acquiring additional hardware.

	- VGA or DBLPAL versions.  Not until I get a VGA or
	  multisync monitor (I'm using a CM8833-II)

	- Sound support.  (Unlikely)

	- Cute animations.  (Unlikely)

  If you have any sugguestions, mail @{"me" link "Authors"}.

@endnode

